03378nam a22004455i 9780773567351DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t19981998xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735673517 a10.1515/97807735673512doi  a(DE-B1597)656921  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a820.9/3821 aBrozyna, Andrea Ebel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLabour, Love, and Prayer :bFemale Piety in Ulster Religious Literature, 1850-1914 /cAndrea Ebel Brozyna. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1998] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (308 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Religion ;v3100tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tSetting the Scene -- t“The Right to Labour, Love, and Pray”: The Cult of Domesticity in Ulster Religious Literature -- tThe Virgin Mary: Model of Christian Female Spirituality -- tWomen of the Bible and the Early Church: Mortal Sinners and Model Saints -- t“A Future of Blessing and Service”: The Moral Education of Ulster Girls -- t“The Wind in Women’s Wings”: Defining Roles for Women in Ulster Protestant Churches -- t“The Cursed Cup Hath Cast Her Down”: Images of Women in Ulster Temperance Literature -- t“She Hath Done What She Could”: The Gendered Construction of Female Piety in Ulster Protestant Women’s Missionary Literature -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliographic Essay -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBrozyna argues that Catholics and Protestants shared very similar views of Christian womanhood. Both lauded the influence of the virtuous Christian woman, used the same female role models from the Bible, and saw the home as the locus of the construction of female piety. Yet each group castigated the other for having antifemale values. Protestants developed the slovenly, drunken "Biddy" as a stereotype of Catholic women and Catholics portrayed Protestant devotional and family life as cold and arid. Observers of present-day Northern Ireland will find these historical contrasts of immediate relevance. An interesting new look at the Irish problem, Love, Labour, and Prayer makes a valuable contribution to the histories of women, Ireland, and religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356735140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773567351423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773567351/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles